overview.content:
Moses is the lead person in this book; thus his words figure in green. His longest spoken part (496 words) is Moses 34. From Moses’ perspective, the most important thing to talk about is God’s extraordinary salvation of the people of Israel from bondage. Here the central theme of the book is stated and restated. Moses begins, "This is a day to remember forever—the day you left Egypt, the place of your slavery." Then three times he reiterates God’s great act of redemption: "Today the Lord has brought you out by the power of his mighty hand . . . With a strong hand, the Lord rescued you from Egypt . . . the power of the Lord’s mighty hand brought us out of Egypt."

God speaks more than anyone else in this book. The longest of his 87 spoken parts is 4,417 words long (God 67)! What motivated God to speak at such great length? His passionate desire is stated at the front end of this long exposition: “Have the people of Israel build me a holy sanctuary so I can live among them” (Exo 25:8). Intimate fellowship and relational proximity with his people is what God desires.

The blue sections of this book reveal an extraordinary cross-section of life in the ancient world. Speakers include two pharaohs, an Egyp-tian princess, Hebrew midwives, court officials, soldiers, magicians, slave drivers, and craftsmen. The voice of the Israelites is heard most often (14 times) as they and their leaders and foremen take an active role in this story. In many ways this book is a family history. Even as God begins to build a redeemed family on earth, we get a unique glimpse into Moses’ own family. Notice all the members of his family that have a speaking part in Exodus:

• His father-in-law, Jethro/Reuel, speaks 10 times;
• His adopted mother, Pharaoh’s daughter, speaks 5 times;
• His brother, Aaron, speaks 4 times;
• His sister, Miriam, speaks twice, as do his future sisters-in-law, Jethro/Reuel’s daughters;
• His wife, Zipporah, speaks once.
